Orange and caramel sauce topping:7 oranges60ml ( cup) water200g caster sugar120g unsalted butter Who will be the next, great South African baker?Sponge:300g unsalted butter300g caster sugar4 extra-large eggsJuice and zest of 4 oranges5ml (1 tsp) orange blossom essence120g (1 cup) semolina or polenta5g (1 tsp) salt15g (1 tbsp) ground cardamom380g ground almonds50g plain flour10g (2 tsp) baking powderOther ingredients:150g marmalade30ml (2 tbsp) water200g chopped pistachios (unsalted) Just desserts: Marmalade loaf cakeMethod:1) Grease and line a deep baking tray. Preheat the oven to 160 C (fan).2) Peel the 7 oranges for the topping and slice into 5mm pieces; cut off the edges to form squares.3) For the caramel sauce, combine the sugar and water in a saucepan over medium heat, stirring to form a paste. Stop stirring and leave on the heat until light brown. Remove from the heat and stir in the butter, a little at a time. Once the butter is incorporated, pour the sauce into the prepared tray.4) Lay the orange slices evenly in the tray, on top of the caramel sauce, and set aside.5) For the sponge, cream the butter and sugar together. Add the eggs one at a time, whisking after each one. Whisk in the orange juice and zest and orange blossom essence. Mix in the polenta, salt, cardamom and ground almonds. Sift in the flour and baking powder. Pour the batter evenly over the orange squares in the baking tray.6) Bake for 40 minutes or until a skewer inserted into the cake comes out clean. Remove from the oven and rest for 5 minutes. Turn out onto a cake board and remove the baking paper.7) Melt the marmalade and water in a saucepan and brush over the cooled cake. Top with the chopped pistachios and serve.Watch 'The Great South African Bake Off' on Tuesdays at 8pm on BBC Lifestyle (DStv channel 174)